    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="824"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d824">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/15250</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2038</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-18">January 18,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received February 1.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Embassy’s
                    telegrams nos. 97, January 15, 11 a.m. and 98, January 15, 1 p.m., on the above
                    subject, and to enclose<note n="9" xml:id="d824fn9">Enclosures not
                        printed.</note> a copy of the Embassy’s note of January 14 to the Foreign
                    Office, together with a copy of a memorandum of conversation of January 15
                    between the Political Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="10"
                        xml:id="d824fn10">K. C. Wu.</note> and the Counselor of this Embassy.<note
                        n="11" xml:id="d824fn11">George Atcheson, Jr.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It will be noted from the memorandum that it was not possible for me to see the
                    Foreign Minister as Dr. Soong was out of town; that Dr. Wu exhibited a feeling
                    of considerable regret over the occurrence of another incident of this nature;
                    and that he said that the Embassy’s <pb facs="1115" n="1101" xml:id="pg_1101"/>
                    note would be brought expeditiously to the Generalissimo<note n="12"
                        xml:id="d824fn12">Chiang Kai-shek, President of the National Government of
                        the Republic of China.</note> and that the Generalissimo would give the
                    closest attention to the matter.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C. E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
